    public abstract class SOCMessageForGame
extends SOCMessage
    This indicates that a SOCMessage type is always about a particular game named in the message, or never about that game.

    Before adding to a per-game message queue, check that getGameName() is not null or SOCMessage.GAME_NONE.

    Most implementing types' constructors will always require a game; some abstract subclasses such as SOCMessageTemplateMi may allow null, leaving the choice to each of their own subclasses. Non-abstract message types must always return a game name or SOCMessage.GAME_NONE from getGameName(), never null.

    Template classes such as SOCMessageTemplateMi are convenient for quickly developing a new message type, but they all implement SOCMessageForGame. If the template classes are used for non-game data with a server, the server will use SOCMessage.GAME_NONE as the "game name".

    1.1.11

    • Method Detail

      • getGameName

        public java.lang.String getGameName()
        Name of game this message is for, if any. Must not be null in a message sent to the server: If message is not about per-game structures or code, use SOCMessage.GAME_NONE.

        At the server, the message treater dispatches incoming SOCMessageForGames based on their getGame():

        • null: Message is ignored
        • SOCMessage.GAME_NONE: Message is handled by SOCServer itself or SOCServerMessageHandler
        • Any other game name: Looks for a game with that name, to dispatch to the GameHandler for that game's type. If no game with that name is found, the message is ignored.
        Returns:
        the name of the game, or SOCMessage.GAME_NONE or (rarely, at client) null if none.

      • toCmd

        public java.lang.String toCmd()
        Description copied from class: SOCMessage
        Converts the contents of this message into a String that can be transferred by a client or server. For a human-readable alternative, see SOCMessage.toString().

        Your message class's required method static SOCMessageSubclass parseDataStr(String) must be able to turn this String back into an instance of the message class.

        For most message types, at most one SOCMessage.sep token is allowed, separating the type ID from the rest of the parameters. For multi-messages (@link SOCMessageMulti}, multiple SOCMessage.sep tokens are allowed. Multi-messages are parsed with: static SOCMessageSubclass parseDataStr(String[])

        Overall conversion from toCmd() format is handled by SOCMessage.toMsg(String), which checks message type ID to call the appropriate class's parseDataStr.

        Specified by:
        toCmd in class SOCMessage

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Description copied from class: SOCMessage
        Simple human-readable delimited representation, used for debug purposes: SOCPutPiece:game=test5|playerNumber=3|pieceType=0|coord=40a
        Could also be used by a SOCServer.recordGameEvent(String, SOCMessage) implementation.

        Within this representation, message parameters should be in same order used by SOCMessage.toCmd() and parseDataStr(..). Should be parseable by SOCMessage.parseMsgStr(String) which calls SOCMessage.stripAttribNames(String), which your class can override if needed.

        Specified by:
        toString in class SOCMessage
